NAME
<style color=#00ffffff size=1>.</style>            scancode - known formats of scan codes

DESCRIPTION
<style color=#00ffffff size=1>.</style>            The scancode interface of <action name=cons(3)>cons(3)</action> provides access to scan
<style color=#00ffffff size=1>.</style>            codes of the primary keyboard. There are as many scan code
<style color=#00ffffff size=1>.</style>            formats as keyboards. Here are some common ones.

Microsoft Windows™ Virtual Key
<style color=#00ffffff size=1>.</style>            The identifier is emu_win32vk, and each scan code is encoded
<style color=#00ffffff size=1>.</style>            in the two byte format specified in <action name=cons(3)>cons(3)</action>. This format is
<style color=#00ffffff size=1>.</style>            used by the Microsoft Windows™ implementation of emu(1E),
<style color=#00ffffff size=1>.</style>            and each scan code is a Virtual Key. See the appropriate
<style color=#00ffffff size=1>.</style>            Microsoft documentation for the meaning of the codes.

X11
<style color=#00ffffff size=1>.</style>            The identifier is emu_x11, and each scan code is encoded in
<style color=#00ffffff size=1>.</style>            the single byte format specified in <action name=cons(3)>cons(3)</action>. This format is
<style color=#00ffffff size=1>.</style>            used by the various Unix/X11 implementations of emu(1E), and
<style color=#00ffffff size=1>.</style>            each scan code is an X11 keycode. See the appropriate X11
<style color=#00ffffff size=1>.</style>            documentation for the meaning of the codes.

SEE ALSO
<style color=#00ffffff size=1>.</style>            <action name=cons(3)>cons(3)</action>

